{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588424"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:07:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:07:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15139"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15139"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.09,0.17,0.29,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7827"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68077"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7827"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53534"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19089"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68077"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUrinary tract infections are commonly caused by uropathogenic strains of \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E that possess specific virulence factors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a virulence factor of \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["All E. coli strains possess P fimbriae","Aerobactin functions in magnesium transport","P fimbriae inhibit epithelial adhesion","Lipopolysaccharide triggers inflammatory responses","Flagella are required for toxin secretion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Elipopolysaccharide triggers inflammatory responses\u003C/strong\u003E. Lipopolysaccharide (LPS) is an endotoxin in the outer membrane that activates toll-like receptor 4, leading to inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll E. coli strains possess P fimbriae\u003C/strong\u003E - Only uropathogenic strains express P fimbriae, which enable urinary tract colonisation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAerobactin functions in magnesium transport\u003C/strong\u003E - Aerobactin is actually a siderophore that acquires iron for bacterial growth\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EP fimbriae inhibit epithelial adhesion\u003C/strong\u003E - P fimbriae actually promote bacterial adherence to uroepithelial cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlagella are required for toxin secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Flagella provide motility and are not involved in toxin production\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUropathogenic \u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E possess multiple virulence factors including adhesins (P fimbriae, type 1 pili), toxins, and iron acquisition systems that enable urinary tract colonisation and infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Escherichia coli requires specific virulence factors to colonise the urinary tract, including P fimbriae and type 1 pili.","Lipopolysaccharide is an endotoxin that triggers inflammatory responses via toll-like receptor 4.","Key virulence factors of uropathogenic E. coli include adhesins, toxins, and iron acquisition systems."],"references":["Sabih A, Leslie SW. Complicated Urinary Tract Infections. 2023 Nov 12. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613784","Bilsen MP, Jongeneel RMH, Schneeberger C, Platteel TN, van Nieuwkoop C, Mody L, Caterino JM, Geerlings SE, K\u00f6ves B, Wagenlehner F, Conroy SP, Visser LG, Lambregts MMC. Definitions of Urinary Tract Infection in Current Research: A Systematic Review. Open Forum Infect Dis. 2023 Jun 27;10(7):ofad332. doi: 10.1093/ofid/ofad332. PMID: 37426954; PMCID: PMC10323732","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Mueller M, Tainter CR. Escherichia coli Infection. 2023 Jul 13. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 33231968.","Pakbin B, Br\u00fcck WM, Rossen JWA. Virulence Factors of Enteric Pathogenic Escherichia coli: A Review. Int J Mol Sci. 2021 Sep 14;22(18):9922. doi: 10.3390/ijms22189922. PMID: 34576083; PMCID: PMC8468683."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53534"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15139"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53534"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T21:34:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-08T21:35:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7827"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68077"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"sel